00:00:28.610 --> 00:00:32.210
JULIAN BEINART: OK, enough
about knowledge of the past,

00:00:32.210 --> 00:00:36.310
be it memory or history.

00:00:36.310 --> 00:00:43.550
We are in a very interesting
space-time capsule.

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:48.470
We have the possibility
of imagining the future,

00:00:48.470 --> 00:00:52.160
or at least contemplating
more and more about how

00:00:52.160 --> 00:00:59.030
one might use even geometry
to associate with minimizing

00:00:59.030 --> 00:01:02.690
the obstacles of the future.

00:01:02.690 --> 00:01:05.990
And we also have the
capacity to look backwards,

00:01:05.990 --> 00:01:12.050
using many techniques, as
showed in these examples.

00:01:12.050 --> 00:01:17.480
This should produce a much
richer set of ideas of urbanism

00:01:17.480 --> 00:01:20.760
than modernism.

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:26.570
It will depend on the genius of
individual interpreters given

00:01:26.570 --> 00:01:29.720
this new scale of things.

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:34.730
What we're not seeing
are overall theories

00:01:34.730 --> 00:01:38.850
of urbanism based an
amalgamation of these two

00:01:38.850 --> 00:01:39.350
ideas--

00:01:42.110 --> 00:01:43.955
forward looking and
backward looking.

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:49.300
Maybe that'll happen.

00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:50.730
Maybe we're still too early.

00:01:53.730 --> 00:01:57.690
We switch now to a discussion
of the relationship

00:01:57.690 --> 00:01:59.625
between public
and private space.

00:02:05.450 --> 00:02:09.860
At first glance, the distinction
between private and public

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:14.630
space is simply a
question of the difference

00:02:14.630 --> 00:02:18.140
between rights and obligations.

00:02:18.140 --> 00:02:22.460
You cannot park
your car on my land,

00:02:22.460 --> 00:02:26.000
because I have the
right of ownership.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.440
But when we get to a
parking lot on Mass Avenue,

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:36.560
it's a contestation between two
of us fighting for public use,

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:38.300
for the use of a public--

00:02:38.300 --> 00:02:42.050
the available space at any time.

00:02:42.050 --> 00:02:44.930
Sometimes we are
very angry that we

00:02:44.930 --> 00:02:49.070
are beaten by a car which
has gotten there first,

00:02:49.070 --> 00:02:51.020
but we have no rights.

00:02:51.020 --> 00:02:53.480
We only have rights
to part if it's free.

00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:02.640
In the same way, we
have rights of behavior

00:03:02.640 --> 00:03:15.840
in our private world which are
not superintended by the law,

00:03:15.840 --> 00:03:20.790
provided we don't hurt
anybody or behave illegally.

00:03:23.400 --> 00:03:28.030
But if I grow
marijuana in my garden,

00:03:28.030 --> 00:03:33.672
and as long as it's seen
as green space, it's OK.

00:03:33.672 --> 00:03:37.680
There are no rules in the
Cambridge Historical Society's

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:41.850
book which says that you're
not allowed to grow marijuana

00:03:41.850 --> 00:03:43.920
in your garden.

00:03:43.920 --> 00:03:48.930
There probably are other
rules which prohibit that.

00:03:51.990 --> 00:03:53.670
There are a number
of other distinctions

00:03:53.670 --> 00:03:57.030
between public and
private and have

00:03:57.030 --> 00:03:58.630
been used at different times.

00:03:58.630 --> 00:04:00.360
I don't want to go into them.

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:04.770
I simply want to look with
you at a number of examples

00:04:04.770 --> 00:04:08.490
where the relationship
between public and private

00:04:08.490 --> 00:04:18.410
is not so clear and where,
if you take a matrix

00:04:18.410 --> 00:04:24.280
and have four headings
to your vertical columns,

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:28.895
the four headings are use,
ownership, access, and meaning.

00:04:31.850 --> 00:04:34.270
Let's look at each
of these categories

00:04:34.270 --> 00:04:37.850
and see what examples
come to mind.

00:04:37.850 --> 00:04:40.450
Under the first, which is use--

00:04:40.450 --> 00:04:43.585
use, ownership,
access, and meaning--

00:04:48.890 --> 00:04:54.590
Richard Sennett gives
an example, in London,

00:04:54.590 --> 00:04:55.820
in the 18th century.

00:05:00.410 --> 00:05:07.640
It was impossible for investors
in shipping and in trade

00:05:07.640 --> 00:05:13.100
to know the outcome
of of a shipping trip

00:05:13.100 --> 00:05:16.100
that they've invested in.

00:05:16.100 --> 00:05:18.570
There was no electronic
communication.

00:05:18.570 --> 00:05:20.480
It took too long
to write letters.

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:24.470
The letters had to
come by ship, anyway.

00:05:24.470 --> 00:05:26.360
So you didn't know
if the pirates had

00:05:26.360 --> 00:05:32.270
got hold of the ship that was
carrying silver back to Spain

00:05:32.270 --> 00:05:39.020
or whether the ship had
been sunk in a hurricane.

00:05:39.020 --> 00:05:41.570
This knowledge was
certainly capable

00:05:41.570 --> 00:05:45.185
of being transmitted verbally
through human beings.

00:05:48.190 --> 00:05:54.670
So near the docks in London,
a coffee bar grew up.

00:05:54.670 --> 00:05:59.680
The coffee bar was
a private entity.

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:05.150
You paid a penny to
enter and sit down.

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:07.060
You weren't able to--

00:06:07.060 --> 00:06:11.080
you had to sit anywhere
that space was available.

00:06:11.080 --> 00:06:12.370
You couldn't reserve space.

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:22.170
It was frequented by sailors who
had this important information

00:06:22.170 --> 00:06:25.170
about their ships.

00:06:25.170 --> 00:06:27.540
So the wealthy and
the poor managed

00:06:27.540 --> 00:06:31.890
to occupy the same space
because of the importance

00:06:31.890 --> 00:06:32.910
of the information.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:38.865
What became of this place?

00:06:47.260 --> 00:06:53.050
Lloyd's of London grew out
of this corner coffee shop.

00:06:53.050 --> 00:06:56.050
The important thing is that
an important public set

00:06:56.050 --> 00:06:58.810
of transactions
could take place,

00:06:58.810 --> 00:07:02.350
but under the shelter of
a private institution.

00:07:11.710 --> 00:07:16.410
If we wish to put our body into
public space, we need security.

00:07:19.010 --> 00:07:23.630
Security is often provided
more by private institutions

00:07:23.630 --> 00:07:24.640
than by public.

00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:30.660
30,000 people on
a summer's night

00:07:30.660 --> 00:07:36.750
occupy the center of Boston only
if they go to the Red Sox game.

00:07:36.750 --> 00:07:40.560
The Red Sox are a
private corporation

00:07:40.560 --> 00:07:43.440
with private security.

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:47.940
MIT has its own security force.

00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:50.310
Harvard has its-- and the
Christian Science Center--

00:07:50.310 --> 00:07:56.835
just going down Mass Avenue,
you would transect a number

00:07:56.835 --> 00:07:59.640
of private authorities.

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:06.030
So there's a principle that
the private sector provides

00:08:06.030 --> 00:08:12.810
a kind of phenomenological and
actual security for the actions

00:08:12.810 --> 00:08:21.040
of public need, such as putting
your body into public space.

00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:23.680
For those people who
have criticized--

00:08:23.680 --> 00:08:25.000
and they're endless.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:28.720
Hannah Arendt, for
instance, Richard Sennett

00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:35.710
criticized the modern world
as promoting isolation

00:08:35.710 --> 00:08:38.770
from the public world--

00:08:38.770 --> 00:08:43.750
narcissism, self-preoccupation,
people locked up

00:08:43.750 --> 00:08:48.010
in their own private
quarters, fed

00:08:48.010 --> 00:08:51.910
by television and
electronic systems

00:08:51.910 --> 00:08:58.870
and not hazarding the danger,
if you want to call it,

00:08:58.870 --> 00:09:02.530
but the adventure,
which is a better word,

00:09:02.530 --> 00:09:06.020
of immersing yourself
into public space.

00:09:06.020 --> 00:09:11.530
So public space doesn't exist,
except in Roger Scruton,

00:09:11.530 --> 00:09:15.400
the British critic's, argument
that public space only

00:09:15.400 --> 00:09:18.190
exists in the street.

00:09:18.190 --> 00:09:24.750
All the rest is an affectation
and an unnecessary affectation.

00:09:24.750 --> 00:09:31.870
The idea of creating a
public space as a Plaza

00:09:31.870 --> 00:09:35.640
is an affectation.

00:09:35.640 --> 00:09:41.170
It's true of contemporary
Tokyo, for instance.

00:09:44.190 --> 00:09:48.930
Public world exists in the
dense stream of connections

00:09:48.930 --> 00:09:50.280
between functions.

00:09:53.560 --> 00:10:01.250
There's no tradition of
public meeting space.

00:10:01.250 --> 00:10:07.370
Where it's been tried in front
of the tall, new metropolitan

00:10:07.370 --> 00:10:10.730
city hall building,
it's a waste of time.

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:19.370
We'll go into the history of
public space in a few minutes.

00:10:22.860 --> 00:10:23.870
We still have time.

00:10:28.050 --> 00:10:41.230
So if we see that
public use can be

00:10:41.230 --> 00:10:48.530
made more appropriate
by private endeavor,

00:10:48.530 --> 00:10:54.270
we have a notion
of sharing of use

00:10:54.270 --> 00:11:03.405
which has always been
true in urbanism.

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:14.820
The agora, which most of
our arguments for public

00:11:14.820 --> 00:11:24.890
communication space rests on,
was a 37-acre piece of messy

00:11:24.890 --> 00:11:30.890
mixtures of monuments,
temples, shoemakers,

00:11:30.890 --> 00:11:36.560
stoas where philosophers like
Socrates sat and engaged young

00:11:36.560 --> 00:11:37.820
men--

00:11:37.820 --> 00:11:40.670
not young women, young men--

00:11:40.670 --> 00:11:46.545
in discourse, even housing.

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:52.550
This is the space of democracy.

00:11:59.190 --> 00:12:05.700
Wycherley, the historian,
writes about it in the same way

00:12:05.700 --> 00:12:12.750
that I've just mentioned it as
a highly dense agglomeration

00:12:12.750 --> 00:12:17.280
of shoemakers, temples,
monuments, none of which

00:12:17.280 --> 00:12:19.140
fit any cardinal pattern.

00:12:23.050 --> 00:12:32.200
There is no assemblage of
items in the buildings, which

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:34.210
sit in relation to any other.

00:12:42.820 --> 00:12:49.330
This is, in one thesis done here
by a [? Marxist ?] [? smart ?]

00:12:49.330 --> 00:12:56.180
student, the result of a kind
of democratic form of rhetoric

00:12:56.180 --> 00:12:58.420
which only allowed
people to speak--

00:12:58.420 --> 00:13:02.860
that's males and not
women and not slave--

00:13:02.860 --> 00:13:06.970
to take part in
discourse through the use

00:13:06.970 --> 00:13:08.285
of a particular language.

00:13:16.550 --> 00:13:21.860
When it became necessary for
people to meet and debate

00:13:21.860 --> 00:13:28.190
propositions later
on, a meeting place

00:13:28.190 --> 00:13:34.280
called the Pnyx was created
separate from the agora.

00:13:34.280 --> 00:13:36.620
The agora was this mixed domain.

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:46.580
Aristotle rejected that
image of the agora.

00:13:46.580 --> 00:13:51.470
For him, a public plane
or public place of meeting

00:13:51.470 --> 00:13:58.700
was a clean, absolutely
minimized environment.

00:13:58.700 --> 00:14:02.883
I should read you the
quotation from him.

00:14:16.210 --> 00:14:23.895
Here-- "The agora in Athens,
far from being architecturally

00:14:23.895 --> 00:14:27.840
impressive, was a jumble
of crowded downtown streets

00:14:27.840 --> 00:14:29.910
and the regular
open spaces where

00:14:29.910 --> 00:14:32.865
shrines and altars, public
buildings and monuments,

00:14:32.865 --> 00:14:39.132
stood in the midst of workshops,
market stalls, and taverns.

00:14:39.132 --> 00:14:42.540
The agora was the haunt of
the dregs of the populace.

00:14:42.540 --> 00:14:47.280
The home of idleness,
vulgarity, and gossip.

00:14:47.280 --> 00:14:51.600
For Aristotle, the
ideal public square

00:14:51.600 --> 00:14:54.780
were that all commercial
activities and all merchants

00:14:54.780 --> 00:15:00.510
and vendors would be exported
to another part of the town.

00:15:00.510 --> 00:15:03.420
Nothing in the agora
may be bought or sold.

00:15:03.420 --> 00:15:05.490
No member of the
lower order may be

00:15:05.490 --> 00:15:08.880
admitted unless summoned by
the" and so on and so on.

00:15:13.090 --> 00:15:17.220
So much of Aristotle's view
of the public meeting space,

00:15:17.220 --> 00:15:20.610
as opposed to the agora,
the Athenian agora,

00:15:20.610 --> 00:15:23.235
has become part of
architectural dogma.

00:15:26.210 --> 00:15:33.140
City Hall Plaza rests on
an Aristotelian assumption

00:15:33.140 --> 00:15:40.190
that there is something absolute
about prior public space

00:15:40.190 --> 00:15:46.990
which is satisfied by whenever
we wish to immerse ourselves

00:15:46.990 --> 00:15:48.590
in bedlam.

00:15:48.590 --> 00:15:52.460
In a metaphysical
condition, we think of it

00:15:52.460 --> 00:15:57.380
as depicting our
public environment

00:15:57.380 --> 00:16:00.620
in gracious and hallowed terms.

00:16:00.620 --> 00:16:02.570
The curious thing
is the pattern,

00:16:02.570 --> 00:16:07.280
the bipolar relationship
between City Hall Plaza

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:10.130
and Faneuil Hall Marketplace.

00:16:10.130 --> 00:16:12.290
Faneuil Hall
Marketplace would be

00:16:12.290 --> 00:16:17.040
the agora in the ideal
connection between the two.

00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:19.550
However, it's not.

00:16:19.550 --> 00:16:24.500
It's a singular high,
upmarket phenomenon

00:16:24.500 --> 00:16:27.500
totally driven by
market conditions,

00:16:27.500 --> 00:16:29.020
at market conditions.

00:16:35.610 --> 00:16:46.620
So we start off with a notion of
the public meeting place, which

00:16:46.620 --> 00:16:53.430
derives from a unique
setting for democracy

00:16:53.430 --> 00:16:58.530
in first century Athens
and has maintained itself

00:16:58.530 --> 00:17:01.215
through deviations
under the Romans.

00:17:04.190 --> 00:17:08.690
There were no elevated
platforms in the agora

00:17:08.690 --> 00:17:10.730
for people to make speeches.

00:17:10.730 --> 00:17:15.520
If you spoke, you spoke from the
same plane as everybody else.

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:19.190
The Romans introduced
in the Forum places

00:17:19.190 --> 00:17:23.869
for people who were
spokesmen, people

00:17:23.869 --> 00:17:29.240
who had particular ability
to make political speeches

00:17:29.240 --> 00:17:33.230
or speeches which
are non-political

00:17:33.230 --> 00:17:35.675
but of specialized nature.

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:41.510
In the examples I
show in the slides

00:17:41.510 --> 00:17:44.630
at the beginning
of next class, you

00:17:44.630 --> 00:17:47.570
will see that the traditional--

00:17:47.570 --> 00:17:54.260
many of the traditional public
squares in small towns in Italy

00:17:54.260 --> 00:18:00.650
were simply based upon
passageways through space, not

00:18:00.650 --> 00:18:04.280
cul-de-sacs of space at all.

00:18:04.280 --> 00:18:12.230
I spent a year in Assisi, living
in Assisi, documenting the town

00:18:12.230 --> 00:18:15.670
and measuring
pedestrian volumes.

00:18:15.670 --> 00:18:20.180
The Piazza del Comune
is exactly that space.

00:18:20.180 --> 00:18:22.310
I'll show you in
some illustrations.

00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:31.290
In the post-telephone
era, the need

00:18:31.290 --> 00:18:35.970
for people to
obtain communication

00:18:35.970 --> 00:18:40.290
by machine-interposed systems
has become another variable.

00:18:45.080 --> 00:18:54.900
What is the most significant
public place built since 1920?

00:18:54.900 --> 00:18:55.530
Anywhere?

00:19:01.270 --> 00:19:04.210
This is part of an urban
tradition, after all.

